\pard\nowidctlpar {\cf0\f0 Growing up without a mother is one tougher thing, then growing up without love is the toughest thing ever.I have never been the one who believes in love, because my childhood was short of nothing but hurt.Most of the times when I\uc0{\u8217}m watching a movie with a love scene, I always routed for heartbreak. I never understood the essence of loving someone except my mom.I even swore to be a priest (Imam) when I grow up; I never imagined myself loving anybody\uc0{\u8217}s daughter.I grew up in that era of Mexican and Palestinian soap opera movies. My favourite was \uc0{\u8216}Tormenta En El Paraiso\uc0{\u8217} translated as Storm Over Paradise, my favourite character Mariana Seoane who acted as the tormenter in the movie; fought and did all that was possible to break up Erick Elias alias Nicolas Bravo and Sara Maldonado alias Aymar who were in love.Well, I think there is not a single day hatred will ever prevail over love. Even in cartoon movies, love still wins; I thought to myself this must have been an effect of William Shakespeare\uc0{\u8217}s Romeo and Juliet or watching too much of Titanic.Most nights I would stand on the balcony and stare up, looking at the stars and wondering how beautiful they are. How a large heavenly body like the moon appears so small yet the science explains that it\uc0{\u8217}s as big as other planets, is a mystery to me just like love was. But sometimes I ask myself, if love is as beautiful as they say it to be, why did they kill Jesus who did nothing but love us? Sounds like hate is bigger than love. This perception changed when I met her, I mean Teresia Njeri aka Terry.One cold morning of January, I was seated in the class. I had just made my comeback to River Jordan Academy-Secondary School after a long spell in boarding school. My sponsor was not able to raise my school fees anymore. I was then forced to come home but after I met with the school director, River Jordan\uc0{\u8217}s director.He allowed me to study until I was able to raise the amount. This allowed me to join the school once more time since I had studied there before. It was like a comeback of the prodigal son.This was me now back again to mixed-day school. That morning after the Monday assembly, we all got to our classes; our class was on the first floor. We climbed the stairs but I was the first one to climb up. I entered the class and occupied my front seat just straight from the class\uc0{\u8217}s main door, I took out my chemistry books; textbook, and exercise book as students were settling down. I was kind of a loner; I didn\uc0{\u8217}t talk much unless I\uc0{\u8217}m spoken to. I\uc0{\u8217}m a certified clown when I get comfortable around people. We sat in five rows and two columns, the first column had three rows then a space in between the first column and the second one. The second column had two rows; we were seventy-five in the class. Next to me was my friend Barasa then Moses on the first row. When I thought everyone was in the class, it then entered this girl who stood apart from the rest of the ladies in our class. As glooming as a flower in the morning sun of the summer. She walked in a bossy manner you would think she was signed with a modeling agency, she sat in the middle of the class. She was ten seats behind me. I tried my best not to look behind, worried about what if our eyes met. I didn\uc0{\u8217}t know how best to react if she smiled at me. I wasn\uc0{\u8217}t ready for her.There was something about her that attracted my heart to hers. It was like trying to rip it out of my chest. She was short, about five feet and six inches. I\uc0{\u8217}m not so sure. Brown with curvy hips and well-placed sitting allowance with sparkling eyes like a shooting star across the dark sky. Brighter than the full moonbeam.Her face was so soft even from a distance one could tell she was made from the softest material of heaven. You would think Beyonce was singing about her when she said \uc0{\u8